Gender: Female
Occupation: Marketing Manager
Ethnicity: Hispanic
Past Medical History: Asthma, eczema, and migraines

Upon further questioning, Sarah reported a history of asthma, eczema, and migraines. She denied any family history of autoimmune diseases. Physical examination revealed a butterfly rash over her face, oral ulcers, and swelling and tenderness in multiple joints.

Name: Sarah Johnson
Age: 32
Gender: Female
Occupation: Freelance writer
Ethnicity: African American
Past Medical History: Asthma, seasonal allergies

Case Report:
Sarah Johnson is a 32-year-old African American female who presented to the hospital with complaints of joint pain, fatigue, and a facial rash. She reported that the symptoms had been ongoing for the past 6 months and had progressively worsened. She also reported experiencing shortness of breath with minimal exertion.

Upon further evaluation, Sarah was diagnosed with systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) based on her clinical presentation and positive antinuclear antibody (ANA) test. She was started on a treatment regimen of hydroxychloroquine, prednisone, and nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs).

Sarah's past medical history was significant for asthma and seasonal allergies, for which she used a rescue inhaler and antihistamines as needed. She denied any family history of autoimmune diseases.

Sarah's treatment was monitored closely, and she responded well to the medications. Her joint pain and fatigue improved significantly, and her facial rash resolved. Her shortness of breath also improved, and she was able to resume her normal activities without difficulty.
